לפעמים הדברים שאנחנו רואים ברשת נראים לנו בלתי אפשריים. 
האמת שגם לנו זה היה נראה, אבל פגשנו את ג׳ורג׳יה וסיכמנו שאנחנו מביאים מתכון לקפקייק והיא הופכת אותו לציור 🤩
ג׳ורג׳יה עלתה מאנגליה לפני 3 שנים (יחד עם רבע מיליון עוקבים באינסטגרם 🤯) וכשמכירים אותה קשה להחליט אם היא יותר יפה או יותר מוכשרת. התארחנו בסטודיו שלה בתל אביב  @bakerstreettlv 
וצילמנו לכם יחד את המתכון ליצירה הזאת… תוך שעה ☺️

לקפקייקס:
כוס וחצי קמח
3/4 כוס סוכר
שקית אבקת אפייה
1/2 כפית מלח
1/3 כוס שמן
1 ביצה L
1/3 כוס חלב

הוראות הכנה:
- נכסה שקעים של תבנית קאפקייקס עם תחתיות
- נכין את הבלילה על ידי עיבוד כל המצרכים עד לקבלת תערובת אחידה.
- טיפ 1: המצרכים צריכים להיות בטמפרטורת החדר- כך מתערבבים בצורה אחידה יותר.
- טיפ 2: על מנת לא לפתח גלוטן, וכן לקבל מרקם פירורי של עוגה בחושה, אנחנו צריכים לעבד לזמן המינימלי. 
- מוזגים מהבלילה אל תוך השקעים שבתבנית עד 3/4 גובה
- אופים למשך 25 דקות על 170 מעלות סטטי.

קרם חמאה:
200 גרם חמאה בטמפ החדר
400 גרם אבקת סוכר
3 כפות חלב

- מתחילים מלהקציף את החמאה עד שמתקבל מרקם אוורירי.
- מוסיפים את אבקת הסוכר ומקציפים יחד עד קרם חלק. מתחילים ממהירות איטית כדי שלא יהיה ענן של סוכר, ואז מעלים עוצמה.
- מוסיפים את החלב ומקציפים עד הטמעה שלו.
- לוקחים חצי כוס מהקרם ושומרים בצד.
- לקרם שנשאר בקערה מוסיפים צבע מאכל, כל פעם בכמות קטנה מאוד (אם תגזימו לא יהיה איך להחזיר את הגלגל, אז עדיף להוסיף במידת הצורך) ונערבב בעזרת לקקן כדי להפוך את התערובת לחלקה ולצבע להיטמע.
- אל הקרם ששמנו בצד נוסיף כפית אבקת קקאו כדי שתהיה כהה מאוד (ניתן להוסיף גם צבע מאכל שחור).
- את התערובת הצבעונית מעבירים לשק זילוף (רצוי להוסיף צנתר חלק) ומזלפים בצורת קצפת.
- מקשטים בסוכריות 
- עוברים עם הקרם הכהה בזרם דק סביב כל קווי המתאר ואז מתקבלת האשליה של הציור.
- מומלץ לנעוץ דובדבן ממותק בראש ולעבור גם סביב קווי המתאר שלו.

ג’ורג’יה מלמדת בסטודיו שלה עוגות מטורפות ויפיפיות, איך ליצור ציפויים מדהימים ולזלף במקצועיות. חובה חובה לכל אוהבי האפייה.

You’ve bought or made this stunning cake and now it’s time to cut it…but HOW?! There’s a few simple rules to follow in order to get the most out of your cake in the cleanest way possible! 

🌸 It’s always easier to cut a cold cake
🌸 Remove the decorations from the cake before cutting and serve separately (easier than cutting through them)
🌸 Cut the cake in strips and use a chopping board to divide into smaller pieces 
🌸 Clean the knife in between cuttings (which I failed to do so here 😂)

Something to remember - cakes go a long way so start off my cutting up to half the cake and then using buttercream or clingfilm to seal the open end to stop it from drying out

Blood Orange Hamantaschen Cake

Happy Purim! My friend @georgiascakes and I made delicious vanilla cake layers, luscious buttercream, and mini blood orange hamantaschen and poof! A new Purim tradition was born. 

For the cake recipe google “Georgias Cakes”, “Buttercream”, and “Sponge Cake” and check out @adeenasussman for the marmalade recipe! 
 
Hamentashen Recipe

Ingredients: 
1 1/2 sticks (180 grams) unsalted butter, softened and cubed
2/3 cup sugar
1 egg
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
2 cups plus 2 tablespoons flour, sifted, plus more as needed
1/2 teaspoon fine sea salt
Blood Orange Marmalade
 
Instructions: 
In the bowl of a stand mixer fitted with the paddle attachment, beat butter and sugar over high speed until fluffy, 3 minutes. Add egg and vanilla, beat until just combined, reduce the speed to low, add flour and salt, and beat until a sticky dough forms, 2 minutes. 
 
Transfer to to a floured work surface. Knead, adding up to 2 tablespoons flour if needed, until smooth but not dry (add water if needed), 2 minutes. Divide into two 5-inch discs, wrap each in plastic, and chill at least 2 hours or up to 48.  
 
Preheat oven to 350°F.  Arrange one of the discs on a lightly floured work surface and roll out to no more than 1/4-inch thickness (1/8 inch is better!), dusting dough with flour flipping to prevent sticking.
 
Use a 2-inch cookie cutter to cut as many rounds as possible from the dough (collect scraps, roll and cut again.) Recipe makes around 23-25 total. Arrange a scant teaspoon of filling into each hamantaschen (resist the urge to overfill!) Repeat with remaining dough discs. 
 
Pick up a hamantaschen and fold in the left side, fold in the right side, then pull up the bottom, folding each side under another to secure the filling. Press the edges to seal, transfer to parchment-lined baking sheets, and bake until golden, 16 to 17 minutes. 
 
Cool completely. Store in an airtight container for up to 5 days (or freeze for up to 3 months).

🍊🩸 BLOOD ORANGE CURD 🩸🍊

Just LOOK at those insides!!! When I can get my hands on these oranges I want to make as much as possible but a curd is always a winner. Perfect for adding as a cake filling or eating on toast. Save this vid and try it with any cirrus fruit!

Recipe below 👇🏼

🍊 2 blood oranges
🍊 100g sugar
🍊 100g egg (or just yolk)
🍊 20g unsalted butter 

- Juice oranges and strain into a bowl
- Add sugar and mix
- Place onto a Bain-Marie and heat until sugar is dissolved
- Break up eggs separately and mix them into the bowl
- Continue slowly heating until the mix is thickened
- Strain again
- Add butter and mix to melt it in
- Transfer to a sterilised jar or container 
- Best kept in the fridge!

🌸Sunday Baking! 🌸

Whats the maximum amount of cakes you’ve made in one go?! 😅

There isn’t such a secret to batch baking but here are top 3 tips:
- Most cake recipes can multiply quite easily but never overfill your mixer! Know how much your mixer can handle (and how much oven space you have) and then make as many cakes as you can!
- Line your tins before baking. It’s a long process so better to do it before the real mess begins
- Dedicate a whole day to baking. Not only is it easier to decorate cakes a day after baking, it makes your whole cake decorating experience so much more organised and enjoyable 🙌🏼

It’s less that a week until Pesach (Passover) so I’ll be doing a mini-series sharing my favourite recipes just in time for the holiday!

First up; CINNAMON BALLS 🔥

I remember making these every year throughout my childhood and they have to be my favourite! They’re so simple to make and mouthwatering-ly delicious too, plus they’re naturally gluten and dairy free too! 

Save this recipe and start getting your Pesach bake on! 🙌🏼

Recipe:
🌸 2 large egg whites
🌸 225g ground almonds 
🌸 125g caster sugar
🌸 1 heaped tsp cinnamon
🌸 1/2 tsp vanilla paste
🌸 Icing sugar to dust

- Whisk egg whites to soft peak
- Mix in all the other ingredients (except the icing sugar)
- Roll into bite sized balls and place onto a baking tray
- Bake at 160°C for about 20 minutes until they start to brown
- Remove them from the oven and dust with icing sugar whilst still warm
- Leave to cool and store in an airtight container for up to one week

Passover Treat #2 - Matzah Rocky Road Cake! 🤩

I’ve adapted my classic rocky road recipe to make this delicious Pesach treat. The matzah actually makes it less sweet than usual which I personally prefer! The best part is that you can make this way ahead of time and keep it in an airtight container in the fridge...but it’s seriously good so you’ll have to hide it from the rest of your family 🤪

Recipe 👇🏼 

🌸 150g dark chocolate
🌸 60g butter
🌸 45g golden syrup
🌸 100g matzah
🌸 50g marshmallow
🌸 25g raisins*
🌸 25g peanuts*

*you can substitute in other nuts/dried fruit!

- Melt chocolate, syrup and butter together
- Combine with the crushed matzah, marshmallows, nuts and raisins and mix until everything is covered in chocolate
- Pour into a lined tin and refrigerate overnight to set (option to add extra decorations either underneath or on top)
- Cut into cubes and serve!

#pesach #passover #passoverrecipes #matzah #rockyroad #chocolate #reelsinstagram #feedfeed

The third recipe of my passover series are classic Coconut Pyramids! If there was a food that reminds me of pesach the most, this is it! ✨

These old school treats bring me back to my childhood, I forgot how delicious they are! I’ve jazzed mine up with an extra drizzling of chocolate but you can decorate them in any way you like. Save this video and recreate these treats in time for the holiday!

Recipe:
🌸 180g desiccated coconut
🌸 180g sugar
🌸 2 egg whites
🌸 1 tbsp melted butter
🌸 1/2 tsp vanilla
🌸 Lemon zest

- Add all the ingredients in a bowl and mix until fully combined
- Use wet hands and mould the mix into pyramid shapes
- Place onto a lined baking tray
- Bake for 15 mins at 180°C until they start turning golden brown
- Leave to cool completely
- Option to decorate with melted chocolate and set in the fridge
- Keep in an airtight container for up to a week

My fourth and final Passover recipe…Matzah Tiramisu! ✨
Usually I don’t go for creamy desserts but oh my gosh was this delicious!!! (Watch ‘till the end to see a second opinion if you don’t believe me😜)

This is my take on this classic dessert. The secret is to let it set in the fridge overnight so the matzah gets nice and soft, so if you make it today it will be good for Seder night tomorrow!

Save this recipe and enjoy during the holidays! 
Chag Sameach 💞 חג שמח!

Recipe:
🌸 300g ricotta cheese
🌸 100g sugar
🌸 2 large, free-range organic eggs*
🌸 200g double cream
🌸 1 heaped tbsp icing sugar
🌸 1/2 tsp vanilla paste
🌸 Instant coffee/espresso
🌸 300ml water
🌸 4-5 pieces of matzah

- Whisk eggs and sugar until light and fluffy
- Add ricotta and mix until smooth
- In a separate bowl, whisk the cream, icing sugar and vanilla until soft peaks
- Fold in the egg mix
- Make a diluted coffee (approx 300ml)
- Dip matzah in the coffee and layer in a dish with the cream mix in between, ending with the cream on top
- Set overnight in the fridge
- Dust with cocoa powder and grated chocolate and enjoy!

*option to cook eggs and sugar over a Bain-Marie

✡️ Florentines ✡️ I’ve teamed up with the amazing @georgiascakes to bring you these cracking cookies. Florentines aren’t a uniquely Jewish dish, but they’re synonymous with a Kiddish (prayers on Shabbat) after synagogue on a Saturday in the UK and sold in Jewish delis across the country. They’re bloody delicious and super easy to veganise. To make, you need:

150g cornflakes (make sure they’re vegan) 
100g glace cherries
125g raisins
75g salted peanuts
60g flaked almonds
1 can of condensed milk (vegan or regular)
250g melted chocolate

-crush your peanuts in a bowl
-add the cornflakes, cherries, raisins, almonds and condensed milk 
-mix until combined then spoon onto a baking tray 
-bake at 180c for 10-15 mins until golden 
-allow to cool then dip in melted chocolate 
-allow chocolate to dry then tuck in 

Enjoy

🍰 My signature sponge cake recipe! 🍰

For those who have followed me since the beginning of my cake decorating journey, you know that I have used the same sponge cake recipe for years. It’s never let me down and the reason for this is my melted butter trick! 

Whilst there are thousands of different cake recipes out there, this one is SO simple to make, sturdy enough for stacking, and also tastes delicious! Of course, this is recipe is featured in my upcoming book, as well as how to adapt the recipe for different flavours and quantities.

Head to the link in my bio to pre-order your copy of my upcoming book, Georgia’s Cakes and see below for my sponge recipe! ✨

For 2 x 6 inch tins:
🌸 250g melted unsalted butter
🌸 250g sugar
🌸 200g (4 medium) eggs 
🌸 250g self raising flour (or 238g plain flour with 12g baking powder)
🌸 1/2 tap vanilla paste

- Combine melted butter and sugar until a thick paste is formed 
- Add eggs and mix in
- Add flour and mix through until smooth
- Fill 2 greased and lined 6 inch/15cm tins
- Bake at 165°C (with fan) or 180°C (no fan) for 40-45 minutes until they are cooked through and spring back to the touch
- Take out the tins and leave to cool completely
- Wrap in clingfilm and leave them at room temperature overnight or freeze up to 3 months!

To celebrate the Jewish new year I’m sharing some of my favourite recipes using some iconic ingredients that are eaten during this time of year. First up; Fig and Almond Tart 🥧

See recipe below 👇🏼

Pastry:
200g flour
5g sugar
2g salt
100g unsalted butter
60g egg
1/2 lemon zest

- Rub all the dry ingredients into the butter until a sand-like consistency
- Add the egg and mix until a dough is formed
- Chill in the fridge for 20 minutes
- Roll out to 1/2cm thick and line a tart tin
- Chill again and blind bake at 180°C for 15 minutes

Frangipan:
115g softened butter
115g sugar
100g egg
115g ground almonds
30g plain flour

- Cream butter and sugar together until soft and fluffy
- Add eggs and mix
- Add ground almonds and flour and fold through

6-8 figs

- Fill the pastry case with the frangipan
- Place the figs 
- Bake for a further 20 minutes
- Brush over fig jam

Pomegranate Ice Cream 🌱🍦

I love pomegranate but when it comes to putting them in desserts it’s not so common. I’m revisiting @nigellalawson’s Pomegranate Ice cream that I made years ago when I started baking. It’s creamy, tart and a perfect refresher at the end of a meal. ✨
I’ve adapted the recipe slightly by reducing the pomegranate juice to a syrup which also intensifies the flavour. 

See recipe below 👇🏼

2 Pomegranates juiced (leave some seeds aside)
Juice of one lime
500ml whipping cream
150g icing sugar
Vanilla 

- Juice the pomegranates and set some seeds aside
- Add the juice of the lime and reduce the juice in a pan until it’s about half the amount
- Leave the syrup to cool completely
- Whip up the cream with the vanilla and sugar until soft peaks
- Fold in most of the syrup 
- Transfer into a container
- Marble through the remaining syrup and top with the leftover seeds
- Freeze for 4 hours or overnight

What’s Rosh Hashanah without honey cake? 🍯🍎

For my third recipe of this series I’ve added a layer of thinly sliced apples to the top of my cake, but this recipe works perfectly well without the apple too. Squidgy, moist and caramel-y, plus one of the easiest cakes to make!

See Recipe below 👇🏼

225g plain flour
1.5 tsp baking powder
1 tsp bicarb soda
1.5 tsp mixed spices
140g sugar
225g runny honey
140g oil
225g boiling water
3 large eggs
1 apple

Syrup:
30g honey
30ml boiling water

- Combine all of the dry ingredients in a large bowl
- Pour in the oil, honey and water and mix through until fully combined 
- Add the eggs and mix through
- Pour into a lined cake tin (I used a 10 inch round cake tin)
- Slice the apples thinly and carefully place onto the surface of the batter
- Bake at 150°C (fan) for 50-60 minutes 
- Combine the honey and water for the syrup and brush over the top of the cake whilst it’s still warm

Enjoy this chocolatey deliciousness 😋

185g butter
185g good quality dark chocolate
3 eggs
275g caster sugar
85g plain flour
40g cocoa powder
1 tsp salt
50g chopped pistachios 
50g white chocolate 
2-3 tsp pistachio paste

- melt chocolate and butter together
- whisk eggs and sugar until ribbon stage
- add chocolate and butter to whisking eggs
- add the sieved flour and cocoa powder and mix through 
- add the white chocolate and most of the pistachios and mix through
- fill a lined tin (I used a 6 inch square tin)
- marble through the pistachio paste
- top off with the rest of the crushed pistachios
- bake for 25 minutes at 180°C
- leave to cool and refrigerate overnight before cutting
